---
// True Refrigeration Repair Los Angeles — HUB
// /brands/true/
// Cluster 02 Commercial Refrigeration · Hub + combo (cross-cluster 3 services: 2+14+16)
// Wraps existing combo at /brands/commercial-refrigeration/true-refrigeration-commercial-repair/
// and cross-track links to /brands/true-residential-refrigerator-repair/
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import BrandBranchesGrid from '../../components/BrandBranchesGrid.astro';
import { MAIN_PHONE, MAIN_PHONE_TEL } from '../../data/branches';

const title = "True Refrigeration Repair | Southern California | Same Day";
const description = "Same-day True T-series, TUC, TSSU, GDM, THAC commercial refrigeration repair across Southern California. Independent American-made since 1945. $120 diag. (424) 325-0520.";
const canonical = "https://samedayappliance.repair/brands/true/";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Is True Refrigeration still American-owned?",
    a: "Yes. True Manufacturing is the Trulaske family's 3rd-generation business, headquartered in O'Fallon, Missouri with a second plant in Abilene, Texas. Founded in 1945 by Robert L. Trulaske Sr. It has never been sold — not to Ali Group, not to ITW, not to Welbilt (now also Ali), not to Hoshizaki, not to a private-equity rollup. That matters for two reasons on a service call. First, parts supply is a single channel straight from O'Fallon, which has been uninterrupted through the industry consolidation wave of 2020-2022 — our techs don't wait on distributor network transitions for True parts the way we do on some post-2022 Ali Group brands. Second, it explains the pricing premium: True holds its pricing at the higher end of the commercial refrigeration market, and we'll tell you that straight when we quote a repair-vs-replace call."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between True T-series, TUC, and TSSU lines?",
    a: "Three distinct product families that our techs service across LA back-of-house equipment lists every week. T-series is the reach-in upright — the default restaurant and institutional walk-up fridge, sized T-19, T-23, T-35, T-49, T-72 by interior cubic feet. TUC is the undercounter line — the worktop and undercounter refrigerators and freezers that live underneath the pass or the prep counter. TSSU is the sandwich-and-salad prep table line — the cold rail with a refrigerated base that sits at the make-line, the piece of equipment that runs about 80% of LA deli, taqueria, and fast-casual prep stations. Different footprints, different refrigeration loads, mostly shared component ecosystem (same compressor platform, same evaporator style, same door hardware family). Our diagnostic approach is identical across all three; the repair economics differ because prep tables see more door cycles per service window than a reach-in does."
  },
  {
    q: "Do you service True glass door merchandisers (GDM) for convenience stores?",
    a: "Yes — GDM, TVM, and GDM-HC are a regular part of our dispatch to 7-Eleven, AMPM, Circle K, Food 4 Less, and independent bodega / liquor store chains across LA. The GDM line is True's glass-door merchandiser (beverage cooler, sandwich cooler, single/two/three-door pass-through). Common repair work: door hinge cartridge replacement after thousands of customer opens, LED lighting driver swaps, gasket replacement on the doors (the most common call), condenser coil cleaning (LA dust and ambient heat pack the condenser fins fast in exposed retail locations), evaporator fan motor replacement, and temperature controller drift. We carry GDM hinge kits, gaskets, and common fan motors on the truck."
  },
  {
    q: "Can you service True back-bar THAC coolers with R-290 propane refrigerant?",
    a: "Yes. R-290 propane (chemical designation: hydrocarbon / HC-suffix True models) is the current-production refrigerant on new THAC and many other True commercial lines — True transitioned much of its commercial reach-in and back-bar catalog to R-290 ahead of the 2025 EPA AIM Act deadlines. R-290 work requires EPA 608 certification plus the hydrocarbon refrigerant training overlay that not every commercial refrigeration tech holds. Our team carries the hydrocarbon endorsement. The service reality: R-290 charge volumes are small (usually under 150 grams per system), leak detection protocol is different (flammable refrigerant, spark-control workspace), and the brazing process requires nitrogen purge. If your THAC unit's serial plate lists R-290 or HC suffix, confirm with your service provider that they hold the hydrocarbon cert before letting anyone touch the sealed system."
  },
  {
    q: "How long should a True reach-in last in an LA restaurant environment?",
    a: "Our field answer after running True service calls across LA for years: 12 to 15 years is typical, 18 to 20 is achievable with bi-annual maintenance, and the single biggest predictor is condenser coil cleanliness in the kitchen environment. True builds the box to last 20-plus years structurally — the panels, the door hardware, the interior cabinet don't wear out. What wears out is the compressor, and what kills the compressor is dust, grease, and LA summer heat restricting condenser airflow. A Koreatown BBQ kitchen or a Valley fast-casual with grease-laden exhaust near the condenser runs closer to 10-12 years before compressor failure. A Westside or DTLA prep kitchen with clean ambient airflow runs 15-18 years on the same unit. We see the difference on every service call and we factor it into repair-vs-replace recommendations."
  },
  {
    q: "Do you stock True parts or order from O'Fallon?",
    a: "Mixed. Our trucks carry True gaskets, common fan motors, door hinge cartridges, LED driver kits for the GDM line, and thermostats for T-series and TUC. That covers maybe 70% of the repair calls we run. For custom parts — specific compressor models, evaporator assemblies, electronic control boards for newer R-290 units, matched-pair condensing units — we order from True's O'Fallon MO or Abilene TX plants via the commercial parts supply channel. Lead time to LA is typically 2-4 business days on stocked parts, 5-7 days on made-to-order. Our techs will diagnose the failure on the first visit, quote the full job with parts availability noted, and schedule the return visit with your operations window. If the unit is holding temperature in a degraded state, we size the repair window against your service calendar rather than your service day."
  },
  {
    q: "What does True commercial refrigeration repair typically cost in LA?",
    a: "Commercial diagnostic is $120, waived when you authorize the repair. Typical repair bands we invoice on True units across LA: door gasket replacement $180-$380 installed; GDM hinge cartridge replacement $240-$480; evaporator fan motor $320-$580; thermostat or electronic controller $220-$460; condenser coil deep cleaning $200-$380; TXV replacement $400-$780; refrigerant recharge (R-404A or R-290) $380-$820; compressor replacement $1,600-$3,800 on standard T-series (higher on larger THAC and custom condensing units). Full cost ranges are in our <a href=\"/price-list/commercial-refrigerator-repair-cost/\">commercial refrigerator repair pricing</a> guide. Our honest repair-vs-replace line on True: under $1,500 on a unit less than 10 years old, fix it — True equipment holds its value and the rest of the unit will outlive the repair. Over $3,000 on a unit 14-plus years old, we'll run the replacement math with you before recommending the compressor swap."
  }
];

const schemaJsons = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "LocalBusiness",
    "@id": canonical + "#business",
    "name": "Same Day Appliance Repair — True Refrigeration Service",
    "image": "https://samedayappliance.repair/images/logo.png",
    "url": canonical,
    "telephone": MAIN_PHONE_TEL,
    "priceRange": "$$$",
    "areaServed": [
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Los Angeles County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Orange County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Ventura County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "San Bernardino County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Riverside County" }
    ]
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Service",
    "serviceType": "True Refrigeration Repair",
    "provider": { "@id": canonical + "#business" },
    "areaServed": [
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Los Angeles County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Orange County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Ventura County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "San Bernardino County" },
      { "@type": "AdministrativeArea", "name": "Riverside County" }
    ],
    "description": "True commercial refrigeration repair across Los Angeles — T-series reach-ins, TUC undercounter, TSSU sandwich prep, GDM glass-door merchandisers, THAC back-bar coolers with R-290 propane. Independent American-made, Trulaske family since 1945. EPA 608 + hydrocarbon refrigerant certified, same-day dispatch.",
    "offers": {
      "@type": "Offer",
      "priceSpecification": {
        "@type": "PriceSpecification",
        "price": "120.00",
        "priceCurrency": "USD",
        "description": "Commercial diagnostic fee, waived with repair"
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": faqs.map(f => ({
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": f.q,
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": f.a.replace(/<[^>]+>/g, '') }
    }))
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
    "itemListElement": [
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://samedayappliance.repair/" },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Brands", "item": "https://samedayappliance.repair/brands/" },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "True Refrigeration", "item": canonical }
    ]
  }
];
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical}>
  <Fragment slot="head-scripts">
    {schemaJsons.map((schema) => (
      <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />
    ))}
  </Fragment>

  <style>
    :root { --red: #C8102E; --black: #0a0a0a; --gray: #f5f5f5; --border: #e2e2e2; --text: #1a1a1a; --muted: #6b6b6b; }
    * { box-sizing: border-box; }
    body { font-family: 'Inter', -apple-system, sans-serif; color: var(--text); line-height: 1.6; }
    a { color: inherit; }
    .call-banner { background: var(--black); color: #fff; padding: 10px 20px; text-align: center; font-size: 14px; }
    .call-banner a.phone-lg { color: #fff; text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 700; margin-left: 8px; }
    .wrap { max-width: 1100px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 24px; }
    .wrap.narrow { max-width: 820px; }
    .hero { background: var(--black); color: #fff; padding: 64px 0 56px; }
    .hero .crumb { font-size: 12px; color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5); margin-bottom: 14px; letter-spacing: 0.04em; }
    .hero .crumb a { color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5); text-decoration: none; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: clamp(30px, 4.5vw, 44px); font-weight: 800; line-height: 1.1; letter-spacing: -0.02em; margin: 0 0 18px; }
    .hero .lede { font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.65; color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.75); max-width: 720px; margin: 0 0 26px; }
    @media (max-width: 860px) { }
    .hero-cta { display: flex; gap: 12px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 24px; }
    .btn { display: inline-block; padding: 13px 24px; border-radius: 6px; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: none; font-size: 15px; }
    .btn-primary { background: var(--red); color: #fff; }
    .btn-ghost { background: transparent; border: 1.5px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.3); color: #fff; }
    .hero-facts { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; }
    .hero-facts li { font-size: 14px; color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.72); padding: 6px 0; border-top: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1); }
    .hero-facts li:first-child { border-top: none; }
    .hero-facts b { color: #fff; font-weight: 600; }
    .aside-card h3 { font-size: 13px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.55); margin: 0 0 14px; }
    .trust-bar { background: var(--red); color: #fff; padding: 12px 24px; }
    .trust-bar .wrap { display: flex; gap: 20px; flex-wrap: wrap; justify-content: center; font-size: 13px; font-weight: 500; }
    .section { padding: 60px 0; }
    .section.alt { background: var(--gray); }
    .section h2 { font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 30px); font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.22; letter-spacing: -0.01em; margin: 0 0 18px; }
    .section p { font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; margin: 0 0 16px; }
    .section p.intro { font-size: 16px; color: var(--muted); margin-bottom: 28px; max-width: 720px; }
    .model-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(250px, 1fr)); gap: 18px; margin-top: 28px; }
    .model-card { background: #fff; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 22px 20px; }
    .section.alt .model-card { background: #fff; }
    .model-card h3 { font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700; margin: 0 0 10px; }
    .model-card p { font-size: 14px; color: var(--muted); margin: 0; line-height: 1.65; }
    .model-card a { color: var(--red); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 500; font-size: 13px; }
    .fact-block { background: #fff; border-left: 4px solid var(--red); padding: 22px 24px; margin-top: 28px; }
    .section.alt .fact-block { background: #fff; border-left-color: var(--red); }
    .fact-block h3 { font-size: 15px; font-weight: 700; margin: 0 0 10px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; color: var(--red); }
    .fact-block p { font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 12px; line-height: 1.7; }
    .fact-block p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
    .area-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(240px, 1fr)); gap: 18px; margin-top: 24px; }
    .area-grid div h4 { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 700; margin: 0 0 6px; color: var(--text); }
    .area-grid div p { font-size: 14px; color: var(--muted); margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; }
    .area-grid div a { color: var(--red); text-decoration: underline; }
    .faq { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); padding: 18px 0; }
    .faq:first-of-type { border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
    .faq summary { font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; list-style: none; padding-right: 24px; position: relative; }
    .faq summary::after { content: "+"; position: absolute; right: 0; top: 0; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 400; color: var(--red); }
    .faq[open] summary::after { content: "−"; }
    .faq p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.75; margin: 12px 0 0; }
    .faq p :global(a) { color: var(--red); text-decoration: underline; }
    .related-links { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 20px 0 0; }
    .related-links li { padding: 10px 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); font-size: 15px; }
    .related-links li:first-child { border-top: none; }
    .related-links a { color: var(--text); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 500; }
    .related-links a:hover { color: var(--red); }
    .bottom-cta { background: var(--black); color: #fff; padding: 60px 0; text-align: center; }
    .bottom-cta h2 { color: #fff; margin-bottom: 14px; }
    .bottom-cta p { color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.65); max-width: 540px; margin: 0 auto 26px; }
    .bottom-cta .cta-row { display: flex; gap: 12px; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  </style>

  <!-- Top call banner -->
  <div class="call-banner">
    <span>True commercial refrigerator down? Call now for same-day service:</span>
    <a href={`tel:${MAIN_PHONE_TEL}`} class="phone-lg">{MAIN_PHONE}</a>
  </div>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="hero"><div class="wrap">
          <div class="crumb"><a href="/">Home</a> › <a href="/brands/">Brands</a> › True Refrigeration</div>
          <h1>True Refrigeration Repair</h1>
          <p class="lede">
            True Manufacturing is the last family-owned top-tier commercial refrigeration maker in North America —
            Trulaske family, O'Fallon Missouri, 1945, never sold through the Ali Group / Welbilt / ITW consolidation
            wave. Our techs service the full True commercial family across LA and the five SoCal counties: T-series
            reach-ins, TUC undercounter, TSSU sandwich prep, GDM glass-door merchandisers, THAC back-bar coolers, and
            the R-290 propane production line. Same-day dispatch, $120 commercial diagnostic waived with the repair,
            EPA 608 with hydrocarbon refrigerant endorsement.
          </p>
          <div class="hero-cta">
            <a href={`tel:${MAIN_PHONE_TEL}`} class="btn btn-primary">Call {MAIN_PHONE}</a>
            <a href="/contact/" class="btn btn-ghost">Request a Visit</a>
          </div>
          <ul class="hero-facts">
            <li><b>Full product family coverage</b> — T, TUC, TSSU, GDM, THAC, and R-290 HC-suffix lines</li>
            <li><b>$120 commercial diagnostic</b> — waived when you authorize the repair</li>
            <li><b>5 branches</b>: West Hollywood · Los Angeles · Thousand Oaks · Pasadena · Irvine</li>
            <li><b>EPA 608 + hydrocarbon cert</b> — R-290 propane refrigerant work handled weekly</li>
          </ul>
        </div></section>

  <BrandBranchesGrid />

  <!-- Trust bar -->
  <section class="trust-bar">
    <div class="wrap">
      <span>CSLB #1138898 · Insured</span>
      <span>Same-day in 5 SoCal counties</span>
      <span>Commercial diagnostic $120 · waived with repair</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- H2 #1 — POSITIONING -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>True Refrigeration — America's #1 independent commercial refrigeration maker</h2>
      <p>
        Every other top-tier commercial refrigeration brand our techs service has been through a corporate roll-up in
        the last five years. Kolpak, Master-Bilt, Nor-Lake, Delfield, Manitowoc, Beverage-Air, Lincoln, Pitco,
        Convotherm, Merrychef — all Ali Group now, most via the $3.5 billion Welbilt acquisition that closed in July
        2022. Traulsen is ITW. Hoshizaki is Japanese-owned. True Refrigeration is the one holdout. Trulaske family,
        three generations, O'Fallon Missouri headquarters with a second plant in Abilene Texas, never sold.
      </p>
      <p>
        That's a positioning fact, not a marketing line. It matters for service because True's parts supply channel
        has been uninterrupted through the entire commercial refrigeration consolidation wave — we don't call a
        distributor and get told "the transition team is still routing orders" the way we do on some post-2022 Ali
        brands. And it matters for the LA operator who bought a True reach-in in 2012 and wants it serviced in 2026:
        the company that built it is still the company that stocks parts for it, using the same model platforms and
        the same service documentation that shipped with it.
      </p>
      <p>
        We service True commercial refrigeration across LA County, Orange County, Ventura, San Bernardino, and
        Riverside — every week, across every product line True builds. The <a href="/brands/commercial-refrigeration/true-refrigeration-commercial-repair/">commercial-refrigeration combo page</a>
        goes deeper on the specific failure modes, model-level technical detail, and service workflow. For True
        Residential (the True-brand refrigerator, beverage center, and wine cooler line that's a separate product
        family on the residential side), see the <a href="/brands/true-residential-refrigerator-repair/">True Residential refrigerator repair page</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- H2 #2 — WHAT WE FIX -->
  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>What our techs fix across the True product family</h2>
      <p class="intro">
        Pattern recognition after running True service calls across LA back-of-house equipment every week. The failure
        modes cluster by product line because the platform architecture is shared across True's commercial family.
      </p>

      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>Reach-in and undercounter (T, TUC)</h3>
        <p>
          Door gasket compression loss first — the line cook notices fog rolling out harder than it used to on a
          Saturday service, or frost builds along the door jamb. Evaporator fan motor failures second — grinding
          bearing noise that preceded the failure by weeks in most cases. Compressor thermal overload trips third,
          almost always traced back to a clogged condenser coil at the bottom grille where LA kitchen dust and grease
          pack fast. We carry gaskets, common fan motor sizes, and hinge hardware on the truck.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>Sandwich and prep tables (TSSU)</h3>
        <p>
          Prep tables work harder than any other True commercial product because the door and the cold-rail lid open
          hundreds of times per service window. Failure pattern: gasket wear on both the base door and the make-line
          rail, followed by drift on the rail temperature (the rail's evaporator is small and sensitive to airflow
          blockage), followed by condenser issues from grease migration. We see these at LA delis from Langer's-era
          institutional operators down to counter-service taquerias in East LA and Boyle Heights.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>Glass-door merchandisers (GDM, TVM)</h3>
        <p>
          LED driver failure is the #1 call on GDM — the lighting driver sits inside the top frame, runs continuously,
          and fails quietly before the customer notices. Door hinge cartridge replacement is #2 — thousands of
          customer opens per week at a 7-Eleven or Circle K chew through the hinge bushings in 18-36 months. Gasket
          replacement and condenser cleaning round out the top four. We keep GDM-specific parts on the truck because
          the call rate is high.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>Back-bar and bottle coolers (THAC, TBB)</h3>
        <p>
          Back-bar coolers at LA bars and craft-cocktail operators run harder than reach-ins — open every 30 seconds
          during Friday and Saturday service. Our techs see gasket failure, door heater failures on freezer-side units,
          and increasingly R-290 propane refrigerant diagnostic work because True transitioned much of the THAC line
          to HC-suffix hydrocarbon refrigerant. That's the EPA 608 hydrocarbon endorsement specialty — not every
          commercial refrigeration tech holds it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- H2 #3 — MODEL MAP -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>The True model map — T, TUC, TSSU, GDM, THAC, TDC</h2>
      <p class="intro">
        True's catalog runs about 40 distinct product families; in LA commercial kitchens, these are the six our techs
        service every week. Each lives in a different spot on the kitchen line and has a distinct refrigeration load
        profile.
      </p>
      <div class="model-grid">
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>T-series — reach-in upright</h3>
          <p>T-19, T-23, T-35, T-49, T-72 by interior cubic feet. The default walk-up commercial fridge. Single,
          two, and three-door configurations.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>TUC — undercounter / worktop</h3>
          <p>Sits under the prep counter or as a worktop surface. Common on LA prep lines where vertical space is tight
          but cold storage at the make-line matters.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>TSSU — sandwich / salad prep</h3>
          <p>Refrigerated base plus cold-rail lid at the make-line. The workhorse of LA deli, taqueria, sushi bar, and
          counter-service prep. The hardest-worked True product in our dispatch.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>GDM / TVM — glass-door merchandiser</h3>
          <p>Beverage cooler, sandwich cooler, pass-through glass-door units. Convenience store and retail cluster —
          7-Eleven, AMPM, Circle K, bodegas, specialty grocers.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>THAC / TBB — back-bar and bottle cooler</h3>
          <p>Under-bar refrigeration for bottle storage and draft-beer adjunct cooling. Current production on R-290
          propane refrigerant. LA bar, craft-cocktail, and restaurant-bar installations.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>TDC — dual-temp display</h3>
          <p>Dual-temperature display case for retail and deli counters. Less common in LA back-of-house, more common
          in full-service deli counters and specialty food retail.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p style="margin-top: 24px;">
        Full combo-level detail on each product family lives on the <a href="/brands/commercial-refrigeration/true-refrigeration-commercial-repair/">commercial refrigeration combo page</a>.
        The combo covers model-by-model repair walkthroughs, error-code tables, and the refrigerant-transition map
        for each line.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- H2 #4 — HERITAGE -->
  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>Independent heritage — Trulaske family, O'Fallon Missouri, since 1945</h2>
      <p>
        Robert L. Trulaske Sr. founded True Manufacturing in St. Louis in 1945 to build a better commercial beverage
        cooler than anything coming out of the post-war industrial refrigeration market. Eighty years later, the
        company is still in the family — his grandchildren run it now — and the main plant moved out to O'Fallon
        Missouri decades ago with a second plant added in Abilene Texas. The executive team, the engineering team,
        the parts supply chain all sit in those two plants.
      </p>
      <p>
        We put this section on the page because SERP content about True is consistently wrong about the ownership.
        Several competitor pages imply True is part of an industrial conglomerate or describe it as "a major commercial
        refrigeration brand" without noting it's independent. That's not accurate, and it's not a trivial distinction
        for the customer. When we quote a repair that involves ordering a part from the manufacturer, True's single
        channel out of Missouri has been reliable through the entire 2020-2022 industry consolidation. That's a
        practical service consideration our dispatch team values when sizing lead times on a repair quote.
      </p>
      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>True vs. Ali Group brands — what it means for service</h3>
        <p>
          Kolpak, Master-Bilt, Nor-Lake, Delfield, Beverage-Air, Manitowoc all share a parts distribution channel now
          under Ali North America. Parts from any of those brands arrive through the same distributor network — one
          account, one invoice. True parts come through True's own channel directly from O'Fallon or Abilene. For a
          single-True-fleet operator that's an advantage. For a mixed-fleet LA restaurant (True reach-in + Kolpak
          walk-in + Manitowoc ice + Champion dishwasher), the Ali single-vendor angle has real operational logic.
          Our techs work both ecosystems and quote accordingly.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- H2 #5 — R-290 -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>R-290 propane refrigerant — True's current-production transition</h2>
      <p>
        The EPA AIM Act set phase-down deadlines on high-GWP hydrofluorocarbon refrigerants starting 2025, and True
        responded by transitioning much of its commercial reach-in, TSSU, GDM, and THAC catalog to R-290 propane
        (hydrocarbon refrigerant, designated "HC" in model suffixes). R-290 has a global warming potential near zero
        and is more energy-efficient than R-404A or R-448A at the temperatures these units run. True was ahead of
        the commercial market on the transition — by 2023 most current-production True commercial units shipped with
        R-290 as standard.
      </p>
      <p>
        Servicing R-290 isn't a normal commercial refrigeration call. EPA 608 certification alone doesn't cover it —
        hydrocarbon refrigerants require an additional training endorsement because R-290 is flammable and the service
        process is different from HFC work. Charge volumes are small (usually under 150 grams per system), leak detection
        uses a hydrocarbon-specific detector, and any brazing on the refrigerant circuit requires a nitrogen purge to
        prevent ignition. Our techs hold the hydrocarbon endorsement; we track our certification renewals against
        True's current-production catalog, because the R-290 call rate only increases as the pre-2022 HFC-suffix units
        age out.
      </p>
      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>How to tell if your True unit is R-290</h3>
        <p>
          Check the serial plate inside the cabinet or on the back of the condensing unit. R-290 units list the
          refrigerant type explicitly (usually "R-290" with a charge weight in grams) and the model number usually
          ends in "HC" (e.g. T-49-HC, TSSU-48-HC, GDM-26-HC). Older units running R-404A or R-134a have no "HC"
          suffix and a larger charge weight. If the plate says R-290 or HC, confirm with your service provider before
          the repair visit that they hold hydrocarbon certification — it's a liability and insurance issue beyond
          just technical capability.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

